  "prompt": "Can students leave after MS in direct PhD programs at IIT's?",
  "response": "Yes, students enrolled in direct PhD programs at Indian Institutes of Technology (IITs) can leave with an MS (Master of Science) degree under certain conditions. This typically depends on the specific regulations of the IIT and the department in which the student is enrolled. \n\nHere are some key points to consider:\n\n1. **Program Structure**: Direct PhD programs at IITs often include coursework and research components. After completing the coursework and meeting specific academic requirements, students may be eligible to receive an MS degree.\n\n2. **Exit Policy**: Many IITs have an \"exit option\" that allows students to leave the program with an MS degree if they decide not to continue with the PhD. This usually requires the student to have completed all necessary coursework and possibly a research project or thesis.\n\n3. **Department-Specific Rules**: The exact rules and requirements can vary by department. Some departments may require students to complete a certain number of credits, submit a thesis, or pass a comprehensive examination before awarding an MS degree.\n\n4. **Application Process**: Students typically need to formally apply for the MS degree and may need to meet with their academic advisor or department head to discuss their intentions.\n\n5. **Timeframe**: The timeframe for leaving with an MS degree can vary. Students usually need to complete at least two years of full-time study, including coursework and research.\n\nIt's important for students to consult their specific department and academic advisor to understand the exact requirements and procedures for leaving a direct PhD program with an MS degree at their respective IIT.",
